Over the years, field work has been performed on different lakes using a variety of techniques with varying accuracies.  Lakes with more recent determinations are generally considered to be more accurate due to better technology and shorter periods of change to present.  Contour data has been conformed to fit lake outlines digitized from the most recent aerial photographs (1m DOQ's 1991-92).  </attraccr>     </attracc>      <logic>Individual contour lines are linear features that form continuous loops without undershoots or overshoots; they appear as polygons but are linear features and thus have no area or perimeter attributes.</logic>     <complete>GIS products have been completed for a group of selected lakes.  Work is proceeding on a lake-by-lake basis following priorities set by DNR Fisheries (funding source for this project).</complete>          <posacc>       <horizpa>         <horizpar>Source layer bath_contln3:  Not specifically assessed </horizpar>       </horizpa>       <vertacc>         <vertaccr>Source layer bath_contln3:  Not specifically assessed </vertaccr>       </vertacc>     </posacc>           <lineage>       <srcinfo>         <srcscale></srcscale>       </srcinfo>       <procstep>         <procdesc>Attribute Lineage for source table BATH_CONTLN3.DBF:  Bathymetric contours were assigned depth values as specified on existing lake contour maps.
